     <font class="TallRed">TuuK, this is too big for a comment<a name="109410135008243402">&nbsp;</a></font>
		<div class="blackjustified" style="background-color:#eeeeee;padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;border-top:3px solid #cccccc;border-bottom:1px solid #333333;border-left:1px solid #cccccc;border-right:1px solid #cccccc;">
          I'm not aware of Linspire (Lindows) having a 64bit edition at the moment, but Linux itself (the kernel) as well as most userspace programs are fully AMD64, 64bit capable.  My solution would be to install Gentoo, compiled from the ground up for a 64bit environment.  The system you're no doubt thinking of would compile code like a hacker on speed, so the increased time investmest of compiling from source would be minimized.  I'd be happy to do it for you if you live nearby, or do it remotely via SSH.  I set up a 64bit Linux installation with Gentoo for a dual Opteron server at work, so it should go smoothly.<br /><br />The emphasis on law latency is understandable, and running the app within Linux (by virtualization or emulation) may be more trouble than it's worth.  This has nothing to do with Linux, it's the nature of the specialized application beast.  That said, you can custom-compile at least two high-quality PC emulators for Linux (bochs and qemu).  I have used both and qemu in particular can be damn speedy.  However, you might want to consider a dual boot.  Even if you only used Linux for non-audio work, or to back up your files on a more reliable file system, I think you would get good use out of it.  I know even my measily Athlon XP 2700 looks slick in custom-compiled Linux, and that dual Opteron server is a beast.  Here's something that can't be said about Windows (at least an edition you'd purchase in your right mind):  If you go SMP with AMD64, Linux with give you all the NUMA love your motherboard has to give  you.  How's that for the acronym game?<br /><br />Yes, the price on the new Socket 939 processors and motherboards will be prohibitively high for at least the next month.  Although, money must not be dear to you if you're thinking of dual PCI Express 6800's in SLI.  Granted, I don't know much of anything about your work, but even I (a fiend of a hardware geek) think that's too much graphical horsepower for digital audio work.  You'd be much better off losing the Athlon 64 FX and going to dual Opterons.  However, I have yet to hear of a dual Opteron board with PCI Express, so that's another conversation entirely.  I stress PCI Express architecture for two main reasons:<br /><blockquote>1) PCI Express is finally starting to come to market, by Q1 2005 we should see some good market saturation of PCI Express parts.  When that happens, PCI (and to some extent, PCI-X) will become the also-ran.  This is because, despite the long history of PCI and the delay to PCI Express inherent in that history, it is an entirely new architecture designed for high bandwidth and low latency.  One that holds much promise, has been eagerly wanted for years (by efficiency nuts like me), and has been desperately needed for the last two years.<br /><br />2) From an arctitectural standpoint, you want PCI Express.  This is already too long, I 'll just point you <a href="http://arstechnica.com/paedia/p/pci-express/pcie-1.html">here</a> for now. </blockquote><br /><br />I'd be happy to discuss configuration, pricing, and parts lists with you via email if you like.  I draw up parts lists (for machines I'm not going to build) for fun, I pretty much had the server's config nailed within seconds.<br />
