				<a name="109441469608743149"></a> 
				NUMA is definitely not an option for HyperThreading.  FYI, "HT" is commonly used for HyperTransport (a bus), HyperThreading is an implementation of SMT (Simultaneous Multi-Threading).<br /><br />What heatsink/fan were you looking at for your CPU?  I use some Zalmans and a Vantec in my rigs, all are great and cost me ~$30 shipped.<br /><br />Serial ATA (also called SATA, SATA/150, SATA I, or ATA150 [by idiots]) has nothing to do with EIDE/ATA drives of old.  Serial ATA is an entirely new bus that's serial (duh) rather than parallel.  A corollary is PCI Express and PCI.  Because of that SATA drives do not share bandwidth, they each get up to ~150MB/sec.<br /><br />Ah, RAID....this is where it gets fun.  RAID stands for Redundant Array of Independent Disks.  Some say it stands for ...<I>Inexpensive</I> Disks, but they're full of it.  You can do RAID with Fiber Channel drives and spend enough to buy a small house, cost has nothing to do with the technology.  RAID's function is determined by which level you use, and I'll outline some common ones for you:<br /><br />    RAID 0: Data Striping - Data is interleaved across multiple drives, improving read performance (and to a lesser degree, write performance).  No fault tolerance exists, data is irretrievable in the instance of drive failure.  At least two drives are needed.<br />    RAID 1: Data Mirroring - Data is mirrored on two drives, making identical copies.  This level is used for complete fault tolerance, but decreases disk performance.  Only two drives can be used (though multiple RAID 1 arrays can co-exist).<br />    RAID 5: Data Striping with Parity -  Like RAID 0, but an additional drive is used to store parity bits for each data stripe (similar to ECC memory).<br />    RAID 0+1: Mirrored Data Striping - Identical RAID 0 arrays are used, one mirroring the other.<br /><br />There are other levels, but those are the most common.  More information can be found <A HREF="http://www.blogger.com/r?http%3A%2F%2Farstechnica.com%2Fpaedia%2Fr%2Fraid-1.html"> here</A>.  Putting the two 40GB drives in a RAID 1 array would certainly protect you against data loss due to drive failure, but it has a somewhat serious shortcoming.  The two drives would be one logical drive to the operating system, so if you were ravaged by a virus both drives would be equally affected.<br /><br />I'll email you shortly about the custom computer stuff.<br /><br />-Robby<br />
